                '## Fitzpatrick Skin Typing\n\n### The 6 Types\n| Type | Characteristics | PMU Considerations |\n|------|----------------|--------------------|\n| I | Very fair, always burns | High pigment retention, visible healing |\n| II | Fair, usually burns | Good retention, moderate healing visibility |\n| III | Medium, sometimes burns | Standard protocols, predictable results |\n| IV | Olive, rarely burns | Warm undertones may shift cool colors |\n| V | Brown, very rarely burns | Pigment may heal cooler, consider warm formulas |\n| VI | Dark brown/black | Ash risk is high, use warm-based pigments exclusively |\n\n### Why This Matters\n- Skin type affects pigment color selection\n- Healing visibility varies dramatically\n- Post-inflammatory hyperpigmentation risk increases with higher types\n- Sun sensitivity recommendations differ by type\n\n### Assessment in Practice\nAlways assess in natural daylight. Check inner forearm, behind the ear, and the treatment area. Document the Fitzpatrick type in the client file.',
